{"variants":[{"traits":[{"interfaceLanguage":"swift"}],"paths":["\/documentation\/cambium\/gettingstarted"]}],"sections":[],"kind":"article","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Build your first Cambium tree by writing a tiny calculator parser."}],"schemaVersion":{"major":0,"minor":3,"patch":0},"metadata":{"role":"article","modules":[{"name":"Cambium"}],"roleHeading":"Article","title":"Getting Started"},"primaryContentSections":[{"kind":"content","content":[{"type":"heading","level":2,"anchor":"Overview","text":"Overview"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"If you’re looking at Cambium, you’re probably writing a parser and"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"considering using concrete syntax trees as its output. We’ll walk"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"through a complete example from defining a language all the way to"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"walking the resulting tree."}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"We’ll support addition and subtraction on integers, with parentheses"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"for grouping. The user is allowed to write nested expressions like"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"code":"1-(2+5)","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":"."}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"The full pipeline:"}]},{"type":"orderedList","items":[{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Define an enumeration of the kinds of tokens (like keywords) and"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"nodes (like “an expression”) that you want in your syntax, and"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"conform it to "},{"code":"CambiumCore\/SyntaxLanguage","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":"."}],"type":"paragraph"}]},{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Create a "},{"code":"CambiumBuilder\/GreenTreeBuilder","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" and call "},{"code":"CambiumBuilder\/GreenTreeBuilder\/startNode(_:)","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":","},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"code":"CambiumBuilder\/GreenTreeBuilder\/token(_:text:)","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":", and"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"code":"CambiumBuilder\/GreenTreeBuilder\/finishNode()","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" from your parser."}],"type":"paragraph"}]},{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Call "},{"code":"CambiumBuilder\/GreenTreeBuilder\/finish()","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" to obtain a "},{"code":"CambiumBuilder\/GreenBuildResult","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":","},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"then call "},{"code":"result.snapshot.makeSyntaxTree()","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" to get a "},{"code":"CambiumCore\/SyntaxTree","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"you can traverse."}],"type":"paragraph"}]}]},{"type":"heading","level":2,"anchor":"Defining-the-language","text":"Defining the language"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"First, list the different parts of your grammar. We use a "},{"code":"UInt32","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":"-backed"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"enum and let the "},{"code":"@CambiumSyntaxKind","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" macro derive every requirement"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"on "},{"code":"CambiumCore\/SyntaxKind","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" for us. Operators and parentheses always render to"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"the same text, so we mark them with "},{"code":"@StaticText","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":"; integers vary"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"between occurrences and stay un-annotated."}]},{"type":"codeListing","code":["import Cambium","import CambiumSyntaxMacros","","@CambiumSyntaxKind","enum CalcKind: UInt32, Sendable {","    \/\/ Tokens","    case integer = 1","    @StaticText(\"+\") case plus = 2","    @StaticText(\"-\") case minus = 3","    @StaticText(\"(\") case lparen = 4","    @StaticText(\")\") case rparen = 5","    @StaticText(\" \") case whitespace = 6","","    \/\/ Nodes","    case expr = 100","    case root = 101","","    \/\/ Sentinels for missing\/error recovery","    case missing = 200","    case error = 201","}"],"syntax":"swift"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Next we tie the kind enum to a language type. Most of the"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"code":"CambiumCore\/SyntaxLanguage","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" requirements have default implementations that work"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"for any "},{"code":"CambiumCore\/SyntaxKind","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":"-conforming enum, so the conformance is short:"}]},{"type":"codeListing","code":["enum Calc: SyntaxLanguage {","    typealias Kind = CalcKind","","    static let rootKind: CalcKind = .root","    static let missingKind: CalcKind = .missing","    static let errorKind: CalcKind = .error","","    \/\/ Stable IDs in case we ever serialize trees.","    static let serializationID = \"com.example.calc\"","    static let serializationVersion: UInt32 = 1","","    \/\/ Trivia and node\/token classification.","    static func isTrivia(_ kind: CalcKind) -> Bool {","        kind == .whitespace","    }","","    static func isNode(_ kind: CalcKind) -> Bool {","        switch kind {","        case .expr, .root, .missing, .error:","            return true","        default:","            return false","        }","    }","","    static func isToken(_ kind: CalcKind) -> Bool {","        !isNode(kind)","    }","}"],"syntax":"swift"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"That’s everything Cambium needs to specialize its generic types for our"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"language. Override "},{"code":"CambiumCore\/SyntaxLanguage\/isNode(_:)","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" and"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"code":"CambiumCore\/SyntaxLanguage\/isToken(_:)","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" when your language has dynamic-text token"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"kinds like "},{"code":"integer","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":"; the default classifier treats static-text kinds as"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"tokens and non-static kinds as nodes."}]},{"type":"heading","level":2,"anchor":"Parsing-into-a-green-tree","text":"Parsing into a green tree"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"For the purposes of this introduction, assume there is a lexer that"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"yields the following tokens:"}]},{"type":"codeListing","code":["enum Token: Equatable {","    \/\/ Number strings are not yet parsed into actual numbers; we","    \/\/ remember the slice of the input that contains their digits.","    case integer(String)","    case plus","    case minus","    case lparen","    case rparen","    case eof","}"],"syntax":"swift"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"A simple "},{"code":"Lexer","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" over a "},{"code":"String","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" is part of the example flow but we"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"won’t show it inline; whatever lexer you have works fine as long as it"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"yields "},{"code":"Token","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":"s in source order. To keep the parser short, these"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"snippets skip whitespace; a production CST parser should append trivia"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"tokens such as "},{"code":".whitespace","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" to keep the tree fully lossless."},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"Let’s wire the lexer up to a parser"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"that owns a "},{"code":"CambiumBuilder\/GreenTreeBuilder","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":":"}]},{"type":"codeListing","code":["struct Parser {","    private var lexer: Lexer","    private var builder: GreenTreeBuilder<Calc>","","    init(input: String) {","        self.lexer = Lexer(input: input)","        self.builder = GreenTreeBuilder<Calc>()","    }","}"],"syntax":"swift"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"In contrast to parsers that return abstract syntax trees, with Cambium"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"the syntax tree nodes for every element of the language grammar have"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"the same type: "},{"code":"CambiumCore\/GreenNode","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" for the inner (“green”) tree and"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"code":"CambiumCore\/SyntaxNodeCursor","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" (with optional "},{"code":"CambiumCore\/SyntaxNodeHandle","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" projection)"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"for the outer (“red”) tree. Different kinds of nodes and tokens are"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"differentiated by their kind tag."}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"You can implement many types of parsers with Cambium. To get a feel for"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"how it works, consider a recursive-descent parser. With a more"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"traditional AST one would define different AST structs for each"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"syntactic category and have parsing functions return the matching AST"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"type. Because Cambium’s syntax trees are untyped, there is no explicit"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"AST representation that the parser would build. Instead, parsing into"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"a CST using the builder follows the source code more closely: you"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"tell Cambium about each new element you enter and every token the"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"parser consumes."}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"The most trivial example is the root parser entry point, which just"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"opens a root node containing the whole expression and finishes it"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"again:"}]},{"type":"codeListing","code":["extension Parser {","    mutating func parse() throws {","        builder.startNode(.root)","        try parseExpr()","        try builder.finishNode()","    }","}"],"syntax":"swift"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"As there isn’t a static AST type to return, the parser is very"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"flexible as to what is part of a node. If the user is editing a struct"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"and has not yet typed a field’s type, the CST node for the struct"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"doesn’t care that its child slot is empty. Similarly, leftover"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"identifiers from a half-deleted field can be a part of the struct"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"node without any modifications to the syntax tree definition. This"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"property is the key to why CSTs are such a good fit as a lossless"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"input representation, which necessitates the syntax tree to mirror the"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"user-specific layout of whitespace and comments around the AST items."}]},{"type":"heading","level":3,"anchor":"Speculative-wrapping-with-checkpoints","text":"Speculative wrapping with checkpoints"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"In our calculator we have to deal with the fact that, when we see a"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"number, the parser doesn’t yet know whether more operations follow."},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"That is, in the expression "},{"code":"1 + 2","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":", the parser only knows it’s looking"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"at a binary operation once it sees the "},{"code":"+","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":". The event-like model of"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"building trees in Cambium implies that when reaching the "},{"code":"+","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":", the"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"parser would already need to have entered a "},{"code":"CalcKind.expr","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" node"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"for the whole input to be part of the expression."}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"To get around this, "},{"code":"CambiumBuilder\/GreenTreeBuilder","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" provides"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"code":"CambiumBuilder\/GreenTreeBuilder\/checkpoint()","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":", which we can call to “remember” the"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"current builder position. Later, when the parser sees the following"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"code":"+","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":", it can wrap everything since the checkpoint inside an"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"code":"CalcKind.expr","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" node using"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"code":"CambiumBuilder\/GreenTreeBuilder\/startNode(at:_:)","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":":"}]},{"type":"codeListing","code":["extension Parser {","    mutating func parseLhs() throws {","        switch try lexer.peek() {","        case .integer(let n):","            _ = try lexer.next()","            try builder.token(.integer, text: n)","","        case .lparen:","            \/\/ Wrap the grouped expression inside a node containing it","            \/\/ and its parentheses.","            builder.startNode(.expr)","            _ = try lexer.next()","            try builder.staticToken(.lparen)","            try parseExpr()","            guard case .rparen = try lexer.next() else {","                throw ParseError.missingRParen","            }","            try builder.staticToken(.rparen)","            try builder.finishNode()","","        case .eof:","            throw ParseError.unexpectedEOF","","        case let other:","            throw ParseError.unexpectedToken(other)","        }","    }","","    mutating func parseExpr() throws {","        \/\/ Remember our current position.","        let beforeExpr = builder.checkpoint()","","        \/\/ Parse the start of the expression.","        try parseLhs()","","        \/\/ Check whether the expression continues with `+ <more>` or","        \/\/ `- <more>`.","        let nextToken = try lexer.peek()","        let opKind: CalcKind","        switch nextToken {","        case .plus:  opKind = .plus","        case .minus: opKind = .minus","        case .rparen, .eof: return","        case let other:","            throw ParseError.unexpectedToken(other)","        }","","        \/\/ If so, retroactively wrap the (already parsed) LHS and the","        \/\/ following RHS inside an `expr` node.","        try builder.startNode(at: beforeExpr, .expr)","        _ = try lexer.next()","        try builder.staticToken(opKind)","        try parseExpr() \/\/ RHS","        try builder.finishNode()","    }","}"],"syntax":"swift"},{"type":"heading","level":3,"anchor":"Static-text-and-dynamic-text-tokens","text":"Static-text and dynamic-text tokens"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Notice the split between"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"code":"CambiumBuilder\/GreenTreeBuilder\/token(_:text:)","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":","},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"code":"CambiumBuilder\/GreenTreeBuilder\/staticToken(_:)","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":", and"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"code":"CambiumBuilder\/GreenTreeBuilder\/missingToken(_:)","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":":"}]},{"type":"unorderedList","items":[{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"code":"CambiumBuilder\/GreenTreeBuilder\/staticToken(_:)","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" only works on kinds whose"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"code":"CambiumCore\/SyntaxLanguage\/staticText(for:)","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" returns non-"},{"code":"nil","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":". The text comes"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"from the language definition; you don’t have to repeat it at the"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"call site."}],"type":"paragraph"}]},{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"code":"CambiumBuilder\/GreenTreeBuilder\/token(_:text:)","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" only works on kinds with"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"no"}],"type":"emphasis"},{"type":"text","text":" static text — typically identifiers and literals. The supplied"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"string is interned in the builder’s "},{"code":"CambiumBuilder\/GreenNodeCache","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":", so two"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"occurrences of the same identifier dedupe to one allocation."}],"type":"paragraph"}]},{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"code":"CambiumBuilder\/GreenTreeBuilder\/missingToken(_:)","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" records a parser-recovered"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"placeholder. It always renders to nothing."}],"type":"paragraph"}]},{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"code":"CambiumBuilder\/GreenTreeBuilder\/largeToken(_:text:)","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" is the right choice for"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"inherently unique payloads like long string literals, where"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"hash-interning would only waste hash work."}],"type":"paragraph"}]}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Mixing them up — for example, calling "},{"code":"token(.plus, text: \"+\")","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" —"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"throws "},{"code":"CambiumBuilder\/GreenTreeBuilderError\/staticKindRequiresStaticToken(_:)","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" so"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"schema mistakes are caught at the call site instead of producing a"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"silently malformed tree."}]},{"type":"heading","level":2,"anchor":"Obtaining-the-parser-result","text":"Obtaining the parser result"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Our parser can now parse our little arithmetic language, but its"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"methods don’t return anything. Where does the syntax tree come from?"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"The answer is "},{"code":"CambiumBuilder\/GreenTreeBuilder\/finish()","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":", which finally consumes"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"the builder and returns a "},{"code":"CambiumBuilder\/GreenBuildResult","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":":"}]},{"type":"codeListing","code":["extension Parser {","    consuming func finish() throws -> GreenBuildResult<Calc> {","        try builder.finish()","    }","}"],"syntax":"swift"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"The result includes the green "},{"code":"CambiumBuilder\/GreenBuildResult\/root","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":", the immutable"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"code":"CambiumBuilder\/GreenBuildResult\/tokenText","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" resolver, and the underlying"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"code":"CambiumBuilder\/GreenNodeCache","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" (accessible via"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"code":"CambiumBuilder\/GreenBuildResult\/intoCache()","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":"). The cache is what lets you preserve"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"structural sharing across reparses — pass it to the next builder via"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"code":"GreenTreeBuilder(cache:)","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" to keep token-key namespace identity"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"stable."}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"To work with the syntax tree, materialize a "},{"code":"CambiumCore\/SyntaxTree","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" from the"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"build result’s "},{"code":"CambiumBuilder\/GreenBuildResult\/snapshot","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":":"}]},{"type":"codeListing","code":["let input = \"11+2-(5+4)\"","var parser = Parser(input: input)","try parser.parse()","","let result = try parser.finish()","let tree = result.snapshot.makeSyntaxTree()"],"syntax":"swift"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"code":"tree","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" is a "},{"code":"~Copyable","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"code":"CambiumCore\/SyntaxTree","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":". To traverse it, hand a closure"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"to "},{"code":"CambiumCore\/SyntaxTree\/withRoot(_:)","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":"; the closure receives a borrowed"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"code":"CambiumCore\/SyntaxNodeCursor","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" on the root."}]},{"type":"heading","level":2,"anchor":"Traversing-the-tree","text":"Traversing the tree"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"The cursor API mirrors how you’d write a recursive-descent walker, but"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"without the per-node allocations. Borrow-on-demand instead of"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"code":"return [Cursor]","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":":"}]},{"type":"codeListing","code":["tree.withRoot { root in","    print(\"root kind: \\(Calc.name(for: root.kind))\")","    print(\"root range: \\(root.textRange)\")","","    root.forEachChild { child in","        print(\" child: \\(Calc.name(for: child.kind)) \\(child.textRange)\")","    }","}"],"syntax":"swift"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"For a depth-first walk over every descendant:"}]},{"type":"codeListing","code":["tree.withRoot { root in","    _ = root.visitPreorder { node in","        \/\/ Return .skipChildren or .stop to control descent.","        print(\"\\(Calc.name(for: node.kind)) \\(node.textRange)\")","        return .continue","    }","}"],"syntax":"swift"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"For a token-aware walk (most editor scenarios), use"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"code":"CambiumCore\/SyntaxNodeCursor\/walkPreorderWithTokens(_:)","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" or"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"code":"CambiumCore\/SyntaxNodeCursor\/tokens(in:_:)","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":"."}]},{"type":"heading","level":3,"anchor":"Reading-text-without-allocating","text":"Reading text without allocating"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Materializing source text as "},{"code":"String","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" is occasionally what you want"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"("},{"code":"CambiumCore\/SyntaxNodeCursor\/makeString()","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":"), but for hot-path scans prefer the"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"borrowed text view:"}]},{"type":"codeListing","code":["tree.withRoot { root in","    root.withText { text in","        if text.contains(0x2B) { \/\/ '+'","            \/\/ ...","        }","    }","}"],"syntax":"swift"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"code":"CambiumCore\/SyntaxText","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" walks the green tree on demand and yields chunks"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"straight from the resolver’s interned bytes — no copies, no"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"allocations unless you ask for a "},{"code":"String","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":"."}]},{"type":"heading","level":3,"anchor":"Promoting-to-a-copyable-Sendable-tree","text":"Promoting to a copyable, Sendable tree"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"code":"SyntaxTree","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" is "},{"code":"~Copyable","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" so traversal stays unambiguous about"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"ownership. When you need to publish a tree to SwiftUI, hand it to a"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"code":"Task","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":", or store it in a long-lived snapshot, promote it to a"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"code":"CambiumCore\/SharedSyntaxTree","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":":"}]},{"type":"codeListing","code":["let shared = tree.intoShared()","","\/\/ Sendable across actors, retained until the last reference is gone.","await Task.detached {","    shared.withRoot { root in","        \/\/ ... background work","    }","}.value"],"syntax":"swift"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"For long-lived references to "},{"type":"emphasis","inlineContent":[{"text":"specific nodes","type":"text"}]},{"type":"text","text":", use"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"code":"CambiumCore\/SharedSyntaxTree\/rootHandle()","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" and"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"code":"CambiumCore\/SyntaxNodeCursor\/makeHandle()","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" to obtain copyable"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"code":"CambiumCore\/SyntaxNodeHandle","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" values that you can store in dictionaries,"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"attach diagnostics to, or send across actors."}]},{"type":"heading","level":2,"anchor":"Editing-a-tree","text":"Editing a tree"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Trees are persistent. To “edit” one, call"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"code":"SharedSyntaxTree.replacing(_:with:cache:)","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" with the handle of the"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"node to replace and a "},{"code":"CambiumCore\/ResolvedGreenNode","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" (or "},{"code":"CambiumBuilder\/GreenTreeSnapshot","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":","},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"or "},{"code":"CambiumBuilder\/GreenBuildResult","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":") of the replacement. The result is a"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"code":"CambiumCore\/ReplacementResult","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" with the new tree and a "},{"code":"CambiumCore\/ReplacementWitness","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"describing the structural change:"}]},{"type":"codeListing","code":["let original = tree.intoShared()","","\/\/ Build a replacement subtree.","var rebuilder = GreenTreeBuilder<Calc>(cache: result.intoCache())","rebuilder.startNode(.expr)","try rebuilder.token(.integer, text: \"42\")","try rebuilder.finishNode()","let replacement = try rebuilder.finish()","let replacementSnapshot = replacement.snapshot","","\/\/ Decide which node to replace — for example, the root's first child.","let target: SyntaxNodeHandle<Calc> = original.withRoot { root in","    root.withFirstChild { $0.makeHandle() }!","}","","var cache = replacement.intoCache()","let edit = try original.replacing(target, with: replacementSnapshot, cache: &cache)","let witness = edit.witness","let next = edit.intoTree()"],"syntax":"swift"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Inspect "},{"code":"witness","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" to translate any v0 references (handles you"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"held before the edit) into v1: "},{"code":"witness.classify(path:)","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" returns a"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"code":"CambiumCore\/ReplacementOutcome","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" telling you whether the path is unchanged, an"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"ancestor of the edit, the replaced node itself, or a descendant of"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"the deleted region."}]},{"type":"heading","level":2,"anchor":"Incremental-parsing","text":"Incremental parsing"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"For an editor that reparses on every keystroke, you don’t want to"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"discard the entire tree each time. The CambiumIncremental module"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"provides:"}]},{"type":"unorderedList","items":[{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"code":"CambiumIncremental\/ParseInput","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" — the bundle of "},{"code":"(textUTF8, edits, previousTree)","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" your"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"parser receives for each parse pass."}],"type":"paragraph"}]},{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"code":"CambiumIncremental\/IncrementalParseSession","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" — long-lived state that aggregates"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"reuse counters and an accepted-reuse log across parses."}],"type":"paragraph"}]},{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"code":"CambiumIncremental\/ReuseOracle","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" — the parser-facing interface that offers candidate"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"subtrees from the previous tree at given offsets."}],"type":"paragraph"}]},{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"code":"CambiumIncremental\/ParseWitness","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" — the post-parse summary: which subtrees were"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"carried over by reference, which regions were freshly parsed."}],"type":"paragraph"}]}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"A typical reparse loop:"}]},{"type":"codeListing","code":["let session = IncrementalParseSession<Calc>()","var sharedTree: SharedSyntaxTree<Calc>? = nil","","\/\/ On each edit:","let input = ParseInput<Calc>(text: newText, edits: edits, previousTree: sharedTree)","let oracle = session.makeReuseOracle(for: input)","","\/\/ Inside your parser, before parsing a node of kind .expr at an old-tree","\/\/ offset that survived edit invalidation:","let accepted = try oracle.withReusableNode(startingAt: oldExprStart, kind: .expr) { reusable in","    \/\/ Capture the witness data before the borrowed cursor leaves scope.","    let oldPath = reusable.childIndexPath()","    let green = reusable.green { $0 }","","    \/\/ Splice the reused subtree into the new tree without re-parsing it.","    try builder.reuseSubtree(reusable)","","    \/\/ The parser\/integrator owns new-path bookkeeping because it knows","    \/\/ where this node is being appended in the output tree.","    return Reuse(green: green, oldPath: oldPath, newPath: newExprPath)","}","","if let accepted {","    session.recordAcceptedReuse(","        oldPath: accepted.oldPath,","        newPath: accepted.newPath,","        green: accepted.green","    )","}","","let result = try builder.finish()","sharedTree = result.snapshot.makeSyntaxTree().intoShared()","","let witness = ParseWitness(","    oldRoot: input.previousTree?.rootGreen,","    newRoot: result.root,","    reusedSubtrees: session.consumeAcceptedReuses()",")"],"syntax":"swift"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"The witness is the right anchor for higher-layer identity tracking:"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"diagnostics, selections, fold state, anything attached to nodes by"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"identity. Cambium does not maintain those mappings itself — it"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"provides the structural primitive and lets you compose the policy"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"appropriate for your editor."}]},{"type":"heading","level":2,"anchor":"AST-Layer","text":"AST Layer"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"While Cambium is built for concrete syntax trees, applications often"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"want to work with either a CST or an AST representation, or freely"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"switch between them. The CambiumASTSupport module gives you the"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"minimal vocabulary to do this: define one "},{"code":"CambiumASTSupport\/TypedSyntaxNode","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":"-conforming"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"type per AST kind, then use "},{"code":"CambiumCore\/SyntaxNodeHandle\/asTyped(_:)","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" and"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"code":"CambiumCore\/SyntaxNodeCursor\/withTyped(_:_:)","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" to safely down-cast generic"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"nodes."}]},{"type":"codeListing","code":["enum ExprNode: TypedSyntaxNode {","    typealias Lang = Calc","    static let rawKind = Calc.rawKind(for: .expr)","}","","if let exprHandle = nodeHandle.asTyped(ExprNode.self) {","    exprHandle.withCursor { exprCursor in","        \/\/ ... statically known to be an expr","    }","}"],"syntax":"swift"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"A grammar-specific layer (likely generated by tooling) is the right","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"place to define one spec type per kind, with kind-specific accessors","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"built on top. Cambium does not ship grammar generators in core — the","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"code":"CambiumASTSupport\/TypedSyntaxNode","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" protocol is the contract that an AST overlay","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"should target.","type":"text"}]},{"type":"heading","level":2,"anchor":"License","text":"License"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Cambium is distributed under the same dual MIT \/ Apache-2.0 license as","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"the upstream ","type":"text"},{"code":"cstree","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" it draws inspiration from.","type":"text"}]}]}],"identifier":{"interfaceLanguage":"swift","url":"doc:\/\/Cambium\/documentation\/Cambium\/GettingStarted"},"hierarchy":{"paths":[["doc:\/\/Cambium\/documentation\/Cambium"]]},"references":{"doc://Cambium/documentation/Cambium":{"title":"Cambium","role":"collection","type":"topic","kind":"symbol","abstract":[{"text":"A Swift-native concrete syntax tree library inspired by Rust’s","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"isActive":true,"identifier":"https:\/\/github.com\/domenicquirl\/cstree","type":"reference"},{"text":".","type":"text"}],"url":"\/documentation\/cambium","identifier":"doc:\/\/Cambium\/documentation\/Cambium"},"https://github.com/domenicquirl/cstree":{"titleInlineContent":[{"code":"cstree","type":"codeVoice"}],"type":"link","identifier":"https:\/\/github.com\/domenicquirl\/cstree","title":"cstree","url":"https:\/\/github.com\/domenicquirl\/cstree"}}}